    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 14th with two primary anchors driving our offensive output. **Junior Caminero** leads the charge with a 73.24 score, benefiting significantly from a soft matchup against the 6.23 xERA of Schultz. His presence in the three-hole, combined with a strong SP skill boost, makes him our premier asset today. **Yordan Alvarez** follows closely at 72.47; despite a minor park penalty, his elite 0.393 xwOBA and favorable platoon split against Lorenzen cement him as a must-start staple. While **Caleb Durbin** sits just behind the tier-one elite, his 61.94 score makes him a high-efficiency play, as he avoids the dangerous arms that have depressed the projections of his teammates.\n\nWe are forced to navigate significant pitching headwinds today, specifically against elite arms like Ragans and Martin. **Trea Turner** (56.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (54.53) both face the daunting 0.00 xERA of Martin; while their raw talent and order positioning keep them in the lineup, they carry a high risk of category suppression. Meanwhile, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (60.49) remains an intriguing start despite a 1.86s pop-time threat behind the plate and a lackluster hitting position. His dynamic platoon advantage outweighs the defensive concerns, keeping him ahead of **Victor Scott II**, who was our most difficult bench decision. **Victor Scott II** (37.77) fell just short of our 40-point efficiency floor due to a deep negative adjustment for the ninth spot in the order and a poor park factor, leaving him as the primary reserve if we require a late-game stolen base infusion.\n\nManagement remains cautious regarding the bottom of the order. Both **Carson Benge** (40.29) and **Hyeseong Kim** (41.82) are skating on the edge of our efficiency threshold; they are active only due to a lack of better depth, as their projections are heavily hampered by weak lineup placement and top-tier opposing starters. We are continuing to monitor the IL status of **Christian Yelich** and the minor league assignment of **Zac Veen**, both of whom remain unavailable. Additionally, we are tracking **Dillon Dingler** (47.55) closely, as his upside is capped by a brutal matchup against Ragans, though his status as a cleanup hitter provides a marginal boost that keeps him ahead of the bench options.",
